<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sharon Calls For New Likud Leadership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sharon Calls For New Likud Leadership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1705134094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1100 GMT 17 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1705134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Knesset Member [MK] Ari'el Sharon says that the 
Likud needs a new leadership, and that an alternative -- of 
which he intends to be a member -- must be created for the 
failed opposition. 
  Interviewed by Qol Yisra'el, Sharon said the struggle was 
being spearheaded by the Council of Jewish Settlements in 
Judaea, Samaria, and Gaza rather than by the Likud, which has 
failed miserably. Sharon said the Likud should get a new 
leadership, capable of waging a democratic and legal struggle in 
the face of danger. 
  Reacting to Sharon's remarks, MK Me'ir Shitrit said that 
most 
Likud voters apparently want peace, and that is why so few of 
them take part in anti-peace demonstrations. He called on 
Sharon to appear before the Likud Central Committee and try to 
muster 75 percent required for the election of a new leadership. 
Shitrit said he will not lend a hand to the ouster of Binyamin 
Netanyahu, who would be called upon to quit the leadership only 
if he fails in the elections. MK Shitrit proposed to Netanyahu 
to consolidate a leadership of five or six people, including 
Ari'el Sharon, to make the Likud leadership's work more 
effective. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

