<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-098 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Inaugurates Optic Fiber, Solar Cell Plant </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Inaugurates Optic Fiber, Solar Cell Plant </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1905143694 Tehran IRNA in English 1427 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1905143694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 19, IRNA -- President Akbar 
Hashemi-Rafsanjani while inaugurating Iran's first plant 
manufacturing optic fiber and solar cells Thursday, said the 
Islamic Republic relied less on foreign currencies during its 
reconstruction era. 
  "The world's situation is such that we can prepare all our 
needed goods from various countries, even from those which are 
enemies of the Islamic revolution," the president said during 
his 3-hour visit to the plant which is affiliated to the 
Ministry of Post, Telephone and Telegraph. Addressing the staff 
of the plant, the president said that all doors were open for 
reconstruction of the country and that "our vigilant people are 
ready to bear hardships to insure the prosperity of their 
children in the future." He pointed to the significance of 
solar energy and energies generated by wind and sea, saying that 
all these types of energy could be generated inside the country. 
"Such energies may not be economical at present but we should 
lay the foundation of this," he added. 
  Referring to the government's investments in martyr Raja'i 
and martyr 'Abbaspur hydroelectric power stations, he said "the 
energy generated by the two power plants is cheap, sustainable 
and safe... fortunately we ourselves build such dams, using 
domestic resources." 
  He said that the optic fiber and solar cells plant, the 
first 
of its kind in Iran, was of great importance in area of using 
solar energy. He said that it was very important that small 
solar power plants be installed in mountainous and rugged rural 
regions where setting up of power transmission lines would be 
uneconomical. 
  President Hashemi-Rafsanjani said though solar energy might 
be more expensive than other types of energies, its advantages 
over other sorts of energies necessiated its use. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

