<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Asad Sees `Wide Differences' With Israel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Asad Sees `Wide Differences' With Israel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1905112094 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 19 May 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM1905112094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Rafiq Khalil al-Ma'luf, Ibrahim Humaydi, and </F>
Salamah Ni'mat: "Damascus: Differences Still Wide; Christopher 
To Return at the End of the Month"] 
  [Excerpt] Washington, Damascus, Amman, Tunis, occupied 
Jerusalem, AL-HAYAH -- The Syrian presidential palace stressed 
at the end of President Hafiz al-Asad's talks with U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher yesterday that 
"differences are still wide" between Syria and Israel over the 
peace process. 
  Christopher departed Damascus for Cairo yesterday afternoon 
where he met with President Husni Mubarak and Egyptian Foreign 
Minister 'Amr Musa. He briefed them on the results of his talks 
with Syrian and Israeli officials. 
  An Egyptian Foreign Ministry spokesman told AL-HAYAH that 
the 
talks focused primarily on the Syrian-Israeli track, which is 
receiving the United States' attention to stress that what it is 
seeking is indeed a comprehensive peace. 
  In Damascus, Christopher held a round of talks with 
President 
al-Asad. 
  In a statement to AL-HAYAH U.S. sources expected Secretary 
Christopher to return to the region at the end of the month to 
resume his role in conveying ideas between the two sides and 
bring their views on a peace solution closer, as Israel 
continues to give precedence to normalization questions, 
confidence-building measures, and security arrangements over the 
withdrawal question. While Syria stresses that the peace process 
begins when Israel is committed to full withdrawal from the 
Golan. Then it would discuss with Israel the question of equal 
security arrangements, relations, and other questions. 
  Al-Asad met with Christopher in the presence of Foreign 
Minister Faruq al-Shar' and Dennis Ross, U.S. coordinator of the 
peace process. Presidential spokesman Jubran Kuriyah announced 
after the meeting, which lasted four hours, that al-Asad had 
been handed a message from President Bill Clinton, "stressing 
the U.S. keenness to continue its efforts to achieve a 
fundamental breakthrough in the peace process. While the Syrian 
president renewed his demand that Israel withdraw from the 
occupied Golan Heights to the 4 June [1967] lines." 
  Kuriyah pointed out that al-Asad "expressed his appreciation 
for U.S. efforts, stressing Syria's keenness to continue the 
peace process to achieve a just and comprehensive solution to 
the Arab-Israeli dispute in accordance with the resolutions of 
international legitimacy and the land for peace principle." 
  He added that "Christopher briefed al-Asad on the results of 
his talks in Israel which demonstrated that the differences are 
still wide because the Israeli stand is far from the foundations 
and requirements of the peace process launched at the Madrid 
conference" in 1991. The presidential spokesman added that the 
Syrian president renewed his country's "position on and 
commitment to the foundations of the peace process based on the 
Security Council resolutions, which commit Israel to full 
withdrawal to the 4 June 1967 lines in order to achieve a just 
and comprehensive solution in the region." Syrian sources have 
said that when Christopher comes to Damascus carrying "Israel's 
agreement to full withdrawal to the 4 June borders, he will have 
brought a key for the launch of a process" toward achieving 
progress in the peace negotiations. While al-Asad stressed the 
existence of "wide differences" between Syria and Israel, 
Israeli radio yesterday spoke about Syria's "flexibility" in its 
peace stands. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60090 </DOCNO>
