<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Group Urges Young To Join Anti-Mubarak Jihad </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Group Urges Young To Join Anti-Mubarak Jihad </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2205164694 Paris AFP in English 1601 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2205164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Asyut, Egypt, May 22 (AFP) -- The outlawed militant 
Islamic group the al-Jama'ah al-Islamiyah has urged young people 
to join the holy war to topple President Husni Mubarak's secular 
government. 
  The appeal for jihad, or holy war, was made in a statement 
distributed after prayers marking Saturday's [21 May] feast of 
'Id al-Adha in the southern Egyptian provinces of Bani Suwayf, 
al-Minya and Asyut. A high police presence in Asyut meant the 
statement was not as widely distributed. 
  "You young people of Islam, what are you waiting for to join 
the march of the jihad, which will never cease," the leaflet 
asked. "The blood (of Islamists) is still flowing in prisons," 
it added referring to the death of the "martyr" 'Abd-al-Harith 
Madani, an Islamic defence lawyer who died in police custody. 
  Initial autopsy reports said he had died from being 
tortured, 
but a later statement from the Interior Ministry said he had 
suffered an asthma attack. 
  The al-Jama'ah has waged a two-year campaign to overthrow 
the 
government in which nearly 400 people have been killed. 
  The al-Jama'ah also denounced the Israel-PLO autonomy accord 
which launched Palestinian self-rule in the Gaza Strip and West 
Bank town of Jericho. In another statement it said the accord 
signed on May 4 in Cairo aimed to "wipe out the Islamic movement 
and give up the Al-Aqsa Mosque" in Jerusalem, one of the holiest 
sites in Islam. 
  The Muslim Brotherhood, tolerated as a religious 
organisation, also denounced the self-rule deal accusing PLO 
leader Yasir 'Arafat of giving in while praising the radical 
Hamas movement, saying "as long as people fight back, there is 
hope." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

