<F P=101> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nation `Punished' for Backing Saddam </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nation `Punished' for Backing Saddam </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205084894 Tehran IRNA in English 0623 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2205084894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 22, IRNA -- A morning daily here Sunday 
[22 May] said that recent developments in Yemen are alarming and 
would jeopardize stability in the region. 
  "Remaining passive observers, regional countries did little 
to stop the crisis, except to make formal bids for unsuccessful 
mediation between former communist South Yemen and former 
conservative North Yemen, which merged in 1990," wrote the daily 
`TEHRAN TIMES.' 
  The two Yemen, said the editorial, were different culturally 
and economically and it was natural that it would have taken 
time for them to be one. Therefore, Yemenis needed moral 
support and economic assistance which they could not receive for 
pure political reasons and because of drastic global changes, 
the article said. 
  "Most observers believe that Yemenis are punished by the 
United States and its allies in the region because of Sanaa's 
support of Saddam Husayn during the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 
August 1990." Naturally, Iran is concerned with events in Yemen 
and recently offered to mediate. "Iran is the only country in 
the region which remains neutral so that Tehran's moves might 
bear fruit." 
  The daily concluded by calling on leaders of Yemen to listen 
to voice of reason and invest all sources at their disposal for 
the reconstruction of their country. "The Yemeni people need 
bread and butter and jobs which can be provided through 
development projects, not bullets." 

</TEXT>

