<H3> <TI>   U.S. Seen Hindering Ties With Turkmenistan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Seen Hindering Ties With Turkmenistan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2205144394 Tehran IRNA in English 1420 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2205144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 22, IRNA -- The U.S. is trying by all 
possible means to hinder the expansion of relations between Iran 
and Turkmenistan, an informed source told IRNA Sunday [22 May]. 
  He said that the U.S., using its influence on oil and gas 
consortium in Turkmenistan, was doing its best to obstruct the 
construction of a pipeline for export of Turkmen gas via Iran 
and Turkey. The source, who asked not to be named, said the 
orders issued by President Niyazov on setting up of a gas 
pipeline to Europe via Iran and Turkey were generally ignored by 
those at the lower part of that country's chain of command 
manily due to obstacles put by Washington. 
  The U.S. has so far created numerous problems for 
Iran-Turkmenistan joint project by exercising its influence. 
The Turkmen minister of oil and gas is said to be one of 
critics of President Niyazov's views, having close links with 
the U.S. Embassy in Moscow. People such as the Turkmen 
minister of oil and gas have recently come out with new 
proposals that the proposed pipeline pass through Azerbaijan and 
Georgia instead of Iran and Turkey. 
  The source said that the Islamic Republic has informed 
President Niyazov through various channels of its 
dissatisfaction with Washington's attempts to block expansion of 
ties between Iran and Turkmenistan. 

</TEXT>

