<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Southern Yemen To Announce Secession From North </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Southern Yemen To Announce Secession From North </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Envoy Comments </H4>

<F P=102> JN2105190694 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1745 GMT 21 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2105190694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Muhammad Salim Basindwah this 
morning received his excellency the Russian Federation's 
ambassador. The ambassador stressed that the Russian Federation 
has supported Yemeni unity since its proclamation, for it 
embodies the ambitions of all Yemeni political and social forces 
and translates their aspirations for consolidating democratic 
values and (?professional) liberties. He said that the Russian 
Federation believed and continues to believe that constructive 
dialogue and political advancement within the framework of 
political pluralism is the ideal approach for bolstering Yemen's 
sovereignty and its international reputation. He said this 
approach is the best solution to all social and economic 
problems facing Yemen. He said that not on any level has Moscow 
considered the possibility of recognizing the new state in 
southern Yemen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

