<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Al-Bid Secession Call Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to Al-Bid Secession Call Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    3 `Leading' YSP Members Comment </H4>

<F P=102> JN2205185994 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1700 GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2205185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Text" of statement issued by members of the Yemeni </F>
Socialist Party Central Committee; place and date not given] 
  [Text] Several leaders of the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] 
Central Committee have issued a statement condemning the 
declaration of secession made by traitor al-Bid and stressing 
that this declaration is a retreat from our people's greatest 
and most important options of unity, democracy, and party and 
political pluralism. Following is the text of the statement: 
  We, along with our people, were surprised by the declaration 
of secession made by the secessionist elements in the YSP 
leadership. We, along with our people, realize that the YSP's 
elements, cadres, and many of its leaders reject, absolutely and 
in principle, this declaration, which does not express our 
party's spirit, principles, and lengthy struggle designed to 
effect both the September and October Yemeni revolutions and the 
Yemeni unity on great 22 May 1990. 
  The declaration of secession is a retreat from our people's 
greatest and most important options of unity, democracy, and 
party and political pluralism. We, as leading elements in the 
YSP and its Central Committee, condemn the declaration of 
secession. We also believe that abidance by the constitution 
and a return to dialogue are the only possible means to end the 
impasse facing our people as a result of the declaration of 
secession. 
  As leading elements in the YSP, we will hold further 
consultations with our party colleagues in order to take a final 
and decisive position on our relationship with the YSP. 
  This statement was signed by brothers 'Abd-al-Bari Tahir, 
'Abdallah Hamid al-'Ulufi, and 'Abdallah Baydar, members of the 
YSP Central Committee. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

