<H4>    Spokesman Denies Fall of 'Ataq </H4>

<F P=102> LD2305091794 Kuwait KUNA in Arabic 0820 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait KUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Kuwait, 23 May (KUNA) -- Radio Sanaa has 
reported that northern troops have managed to control Shabwah 
Governorate and its districts which are rich with oil and that 
they are advancing to the southern part, which declared 
secession from Yemen last Saturday. Radio Sanaa, which is 
received here, quoted a military source as saying that the 
northern troops in the eastern Shabwah axis have captured the 
military base and the central axis command headquarters in the 
city of 'Ataq, the capital of the province, with all its 
districts and all its military installations. These reports, 
which are considered an important development that would deprive 
the southern part of its important military and economic 
resources, have not been confirmed. [passage omitted] 
  The military source said that northern troops have seized a 
large quantity of weapons, ammunition, and military depots in 
Shabwah Governorate. [passage omitted] 
  A southern military spokesman today denied reports that 
'Ataq 
military base, the capital of Shabwah Province, has fallen to 
northern forces. Aden radio, received here, quoted the 
spokesman as saying that northern troops are not in control of 
Shabwah Province, and that the news announced by Sanaa is 
totally unfounded. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

