<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wrapup of Reaction to al-Bid Secession Attempt Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wrapup of Reaction to al-Bid Secession Attempt Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Revolutionary Democratic Party Comments </H4>

<F P=102> JN2405154394 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
1458 GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2405154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Yemeni Revolutionary Democratic Party [RDP] has 
condemned al-Bid's secession declaration. The party said in a 
statement that it is considered a blatant violation of the 
Constitution of our Republic of Yemen and the legitimacy 
announced on 27 April 1993. The statement notes the RDP's 
rejection of all calls for secession and its support for and 
call on the forces of constitutional legitimacy not to be 
lenient with this rancorous separatist clique. The party said 
that its support for the forces of constitutional legitimacy 
stems from the party's adherence to Yemeni unity, which is 
considered the result of the efforts and struggle of all honest 
Yemeni strugglers. The party stressed that its stand is firm 
and clear in terms of safeguarding the national constants, 
particularly unity, democracy, and the achievements of the 16 
September and 24 October revolutions. 
  The RDP's statement urges brothers and friends to stand at 
the side of the legitimate leadership to preserve these 
achievements, particularly Yemeni unity. The statement notes 
that al-Bid's criminal attempts to destroy Aden and some 
southern and eastern governorates are a continuation of the 
destruction inflicted on brave Aden in the January events 
[reference to 13 January 1986] to satisfy his destructive whims 
and those of his clique. 
  The statement urges all national and political forces and 
our 
masses to stand at the side of constitutional legitimacy and its 
leadership and to render all support for this leadership. 
  This was issued by the Revolutionary Democratic Party. 

</TEXT>

