<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin To Demand 'Arafat's Written Commitment to Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin To Demand 'Arafat's Written Commitment to Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Adviser Differs With Rabin </H4>

<F P=102> TA2305185494 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1700 GMT 23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2305185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone report by political correspondent 'Imanu'el Rosen </F>
at the Knesset -- live] 
  [Excerpt] [Announcer] Jacques Neriya, the prime 
minister's political adviser, has leveled criticism at what he 
terms picking on trivial details and at the government's being 
swayed by the right wing. Our political correspondent 'Imanu'el 
Rosen is at the Knesset. Good evening 'Imanu'el. What is the 
meaning of the Israeli threat to defer the negotiations? Is it 
not a fact that the Gaza and Jericho autonomy are not going to 
be deferred? 
  [Rosen] Since it is obvious to everyone that the Gaza and 
Jericho agreement cannot be taken back to square one, Israel is 
threatening with whatever it can. But since no date has been set 
for the next stage of the negotiations, the so-called early 
empowerment [preceding two words in English] in the West Bank, 
the threat is not too critical or daunting. 
  Tonight we heard Jacques Neriya, the prime minister's 
political adviser, utter some very intriguing criticism, which 
can be interpreted as criticism of the prime minister himself. 
Neriya told us tonight: They are picking on trivial things; 
you cannot expect 'Arafat to reiterate his commitment every day; 
everyone is aware of the importance of the spoken word in the 
Arab world. Neriya further said: They are being swept by 
public trends, perhaps even by the right wing. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

